Strict, hand-authored source dictionary for a Plover steno-to-code plugin, parsed by `src/parse.ts` into the JS/TS Plover dictionary. It supersedes `snippets.txt` (kept as the human-readable companion) — any new entry or template change belongs here, not there, and must stay consistent with whatever `parse.ts` expects for directive names and operator syntax.

Entry shape: a fenced block opens with a stroke (or `stroke1/stroke2` chained outline) and closes with a matching fence; the text between fences is the template body. An optional `###Comment` line above the fence is a human label, not parsed for behavior. Directive lines immediately following a block (`@count`, `@arity`, `@multiline`, `@fuse`, `@type`, `@noarg`, `@literal`) attach to that entry only.

Template operators a parser/editor must handle: `%0`-`%9` are tabstop/landing points (plain entries land on `%0`; snippet-mode entries use the rest as tabstops in order). `%d` is the in-scope repeat count emitted as a literal digit — outside a `%[...]%]` repeat it's the total count, inside one it's the iteration index; it is never a cursor landing site. `%t` is a type-slot filled by appending a second, `@type`-marked stroke to the outline (chained with `/`). `%b` is a body-break flag: all `%b` occurrences in one translation toggle together, controlling one-line vs multi-line rendering. `%p` is a pattern-slot (used sparingly). `%[sep|body%]` repeats `body` for the in-scope count, joining with `sep`, which is suppressed after the final iteration. `%(EXPR)` computes a landing point from a linear expression in `d` (the repeat index) — used by `switCH`/`switCH Default` to produce alternating `case`/body slot numbers (`%(2d+1)`, `%(2d+2)`); expressions are not renumbered by the parser, so overlapping outputs from two `%(...)` in the same entry are a hard error. Literal chars `\n \t \{ \} \% \| \\ \`` are backslash-escaped.

Directive semantics an editor must respect: `@count BANK` binds the entry's repeat/slot count to a steno letter bank (e.g. `AOE`, `AO`) appended to the base stroke — changing the bank changes how many count-variants exist and what steno chord selects each count. `@arity N` (types only) means the type stays non-terminal until N further type-strokes are chained onto it (e.g. `Map`/`PH` needs 2 appended types); default arity is 0. `@noarg` types are terminal with no possible arguments (e.g. `null`, `undefined`, `void`, `function`). `@fuse` (on function-family entries) means the appended type stroke's output is merged directly into the function's return-type slot rather than requiring a separate type-less stroke first. `@multiline` forces multi-line rendering regardless of `%b` toggle state — used only by the two `switCH` entries whose repeat body contains literal `\n`. `@literal` (data-structure entries) marks the block as verbatim class-source text with no `%`-operators processed at all — these are large fixed TS class bodies (LinkedList, Stack, Queue, Deque, MinHeap/MaxHeap, BinaryTree, BST, Graph, Trie) selected by root stroke `STKWR-RBGT` plus a selector suffix; editing one requires preserving valid, self-contained TypeScript since nothing else post-processes it.

Structural conventions to know before editing: type strokes (`TPH`=number, `STR`=string, `PW`=boolean, `PR`=Promise, `PH`=Map, `KR`=Record, `ST`=Set, `R`=Array, `SKWR`=Generator, etc.) are non-terminal building blocks, invalid standalone, and are appended via `/` to a preceding entry's stroke to fill its `%t`; `STKWR-T` is the generic "type emitter" root that turns any appended type into a free-floating annotation/cast. The array/string/math "callback method-root" family (`STKWR*PLT` + method selector, e.g. `/R-PL` for `.map`) always has a paired `*`-suffixed sibling stroke that swaps the arrow-body for a `{return ...}` block — the block variant's `\n` is literal (not `%b`) since block form implies multi-line by definition. Params (`STKWR-PB` bare, `STKWR-PT` typed) are designed to be dropped inside an already-open `()` — they emit no parens themselves. Comments in this file use `#` or `//`; both are stripped by the parser and carry no semantic weight.